text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!Voicing in Plosives: Comparing English and Mandarin Chinese%0a%0a:Author: annie31%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aVoicing in Plosives: Comparing English and Mandarin Chinese%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aVoicing in Plosives: Comparing English and Mandarin Chinese%0a%0aBelonging to the obstruents group, plosives are pronounced by blocking the airflow from exiting the mouth to some extent. [1] Voicing, on the other hand, describes the vibration of “airflow over vocal folds.” [2] While pronouncing voiced sounds requires airflow for vibration, plosives simply stop the airflow: due to the contradiction, only some languages have voiced plosives. [3]%0a%0aIn English, plosives can be voiced or voiceless. [4] For the voiceless plosives [p, t, k], the vocal folds are “pulled apart” when “the oral constriction” is made; for the voiced plosives [b, d, g], the vocal folds are “held together throughout” so voicing can “continue through the constriction.” [5] On the other side, Mandarin Chinese only has voiceless plosives, which are subdivided into unaspirated ones and aspirated ones. [6] Similar to English, the unaspirated voiceless plosives in Mandarin Chinese are [p, t, k]. To draw a difference, in the IPA chart, the aspirated voiceless plosives [ph, th, kh] are denoted with an “h” on the top right corner. [7]%0a%0aComparing the composition of word in the two languages, a main distinguishing point would be the arrangements of consonants (C) and vowels (V). English offers multiple syllable structures ranging from the simple V to the complex CCCVCCC, and plosives can be placed either before or after the vowel. In contrast, syllable structures in Mandarin Chinese consists of “an optional initial consonant + vowel (accompanied by tone) + optional final consonant (n or ng),” [8] which implies that plosives only appear as word initials. Taking syllable structure into account, perhaps the arrangements of plosives (whether word-initials or not) can explain why Mandarin Chinese leaves out voiced plosives.%0a%0aReference%0a[1] Zsiga, E. C. (2013). The Sounds of Language: An Introduction to Phonetics and Phonology. Wiley-Blackwell.%0a[2] IBID.%0a[3] IBID.%0a[4] The World Atlas of Language Structures Online. (n.d.). Datapoint English / Voicing in Plosives and Fricatives. Retrieved September 29, 2022, from https://wals.info/valuesets/4A-eng%0a[5] Zsiga, E. C. (2013). The Sounds of Language: An Introduction to Phonetics and Phonology. Wiley-Blackwell.%0a[6] The World Atlas of Language Structures Online. (n.d.). Datapoint Mandarin / Voicing in Plosives and Fricatives. Retrieved September 29, 2022, from https://wals.info/valuesets/4A-mnd%0a[7] PHOIBLE 2.0. (2019). Inventory Standard Chinese (Beijing). Retrieved September 29, 2022, from https://phoible.org/inventories/view/2457%0a[8] MustGo About World Languages. (n.d.). Mandarin (Chinese). https://www.mustgo.com/worldlanguages/mandarin/%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%