e IPA chart, the aspirated voiceless plosives [ph, th, kh] are denoted with an “h” on the top right corner.%0a%3c %0a%3c Comparing the composition of word in the two languages, a main distinguishing point would be the arrangements of consonants (C) and vowels (V). While English offers multiple syllable structure ranging from the simple V to the complex CCCVCCC, Mandarin Chinese only has V and CV. Taking syllable structure into account, perhaps word-initial consonants can explain why Mandarin Chinese leaves out voiced plosives.%0a%3c %0a%3c Reference%0a%3c [1] Zsiga, E. C. (2013). The Sounds of Language: An Introduction to Phonetics and Phonology. Wiley-Blackwell.%0a%3c [2] IBID.%0a%3c [3] IBID.%0a%3c [4] The World Atlas of Language Structures Online. (n.d.). Datapoint English / Voicing in Plosives and Fricatives. Retrieved September 29, 2022, from https://wals.info/valuesets/4A-eng%0a%3c [5] Zsiga, E. C. (2013). The Sounds of Language: An Introduction to Phonetics and Phonology. Wiley-Blackwell.%0a%3c [6] The World Atlas of Language Structures Online. (n.d.). Datapoint Mandarin / Voicing in Plosives and Fricatives. Retrieved September 29, 2022, from https://wals.info/valuesets/4A-mnd%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c You must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a%3c !!Change article category%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#change